[[File:BandoKarte Adressbuch1917-8 de.PNG|thumb|right|Plan of the camp in 1917]] [[File:Doitsu-bashi.jpeg|thumb|right|German Bridge, built by the prisoners of Bandō during their captivity]] [[File:140712 Baruto-no-niwa in Bando Naruto Tokushima pref Japan01bs5.jpg|thumb|right|The museum of the history of Bandō prisoner-of-war camp "Baruto-no-niwa" in [[Naruto, Tokushima|Naruto]].]] The {{nihongo|'''Bandō POW camp'''|板東俘虜収容所|Bandō Furyoshūyōsho}} was a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] during [[World War I]] in what is now [[Naruto, Tokushima|Naruto]], [[Tokushima Prefecture]], Shikoku Island, [[Japan]]. From April 1917 to January 1920, just under a thousand of the three thousand nine hundred German soldiers captured at [[Qingdao|Tsingtao]], China in November 1914 were imprisoned at the camp. When the camp closed in 1920, sixty-three of the prisoners chose to remain in Japan.<ref name="Times">{{cite news |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn20060613f1.html |title=Bando POW camp: chivalry's last bastion |author=Johnston, Eric |publisher=[[The Japan Times]] |date=13 June 2006 |accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>
==Orchestra== During their internment the prisoners formed an orchestra which performed over a hundred concerts between 1917 and 1920, including at nearby [[Ryōzen-ji (Naruto)|Ryōzen-ji]].<ref name="Times"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.netsamurai.de/netplanet-harburg/schaarmann/Heimat-Bando-Dokumentation-Werner-Schaarmann-2009.pdf |title=Heimat Bando (historic photographs) |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref> On 1 June 1918 the prisoners mounted the first performance of [[Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Ninth Symphony]] in the country. This event is the origin of the popularity of the symphony in Japan, performed numerous times at the end of each year, and is celebrated annually with a concert at the Naruto Bunka Kaikan on the first Sunday in June.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20101224r1.html |title=Japan makes Beethoven's Ninth No. 1 for the holidays |author=Brasor, Philip |work=[[The Japan Times]] |date=24 December 2010 |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.naruto.tokushima.jp/contents/foreign/english/annual_events.html |title=Annual Events in Naruto |publisher=[[Naruto, Tokushima|Naruto City]] |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref>
==German House== The {{nihongo|Naruto Doitsu-kan|鳴門市ドイツ館}} museum opened in 1972 to exhibit related items. In 1974 Naruto was twinned with [[Lüneburg]] in Germany and the subsequent accession of further materials necessitated the move to new premises. A new building near the former camp opened in 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.naruto.tokushima.jp/contents/foreign/english/cultural_facilities.html |title=Cultural & Tourist Facilities - German House (Doitsu-kan) |publisher=[[Naruto, Tokushima|Naruto City]] |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref>
